g ‘break bread’, from a dialect word <i>sfragari</i> ‘to break’; or a variant of <b>Fregapane</b>, a nickname probably from a phrase meaning ‘steal bread’."]}]},{"name":"Una","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Irish Úna . In Irish legend Úna is the mother of the hero Conn Cétchathach (Conn of the Hundred Battles). It was also the name of the beloved of the 17th-century poet  Tomás Láidir Costello : banned by her parents from seeing him, Úna fell into a decline and died, leaving him to mourn her in his verse. The Anglicized form of the name is sometimes taken to be from the feminine of Latin <i>unus</i> ‘one’. It is the name used by Spenser for the lady of the Red Cross Knight in The Faerie Queene: he probably had Latin rather than Irish in mind, even though he worked in Ireland for a while. The Irish name has also been Anglicized as   Unity  ,   Juno  ,   Winifred  , and   Agnes ."],"variants":[{"name":"Euna","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Ùna ."]},{"name":"Oona","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Oonagh","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Úna ."]},{"name":"Juno","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Irish name Úna , assimilated to the name of the Roman goddess <i>Juno</i>, consort of Jupiter."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Una Frangipane was born in 1145, in Correggio, Ferrara, Ferrara, Emilia-Romagna, Italy as the daughter of Frangipani. She married Moroello Malaspina. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died on 29 July 1202, in her hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1145–22 Jul 1202":"1145–29. juuli 1202","1040–1127":"1040–1127","1102–1163":"1102–1163","1120–1177":"1120–1177","1145–1202":"1145–1202","1145–1210":"1145–1210","–1217":"–1217","–1499":"–1499","–Male":"Surnud","1140–1197":"1140–1197","1165–1206":"1165–1206","1171–1220":"1171–1220","1172–1193":"1172–1193","–1225":"–1225","22 Jul 1202":"29. juuli 1202","1165":"1165",